Hmm. Let me look at the problem from a completely different angle. 

The core of the issue is that body text which happens to repeat across pages at the same position gets identified as footer/header content. The spatial filter then doesn't catch it because the note text is in the bottom 1/3 of the page.

What if the fix focuses on the **spatial proximity between elements on the same page**? If two elements on the same page are both being considered as footer content, they should be close to each other AND close to the page bottom.

Here's my revised approach for `filterHeaderOrFooterContents`:
1. Compute the distance of the closest element to the page edge
2. Only include elements that are within a certain multiple of that distance

For example, if the closest footer element is at topY=44 (bottomY=35), and the next candidate is at topY=135 (bottomY=100), the gap between them is ~65 units. We could check: `candidate.topY <= first.topY + threshold` or `candidate.bottomY <= first.bottomY + threshold`.

