private static List<IObject> filterHeaderOrFooterContents(List<IObject> contents, int pageNumber, boolean isHeaderDetection) {
    BoundingBox boundingBox = DocumentProcessor.getPageBoundingBox(pageNumber);
    if (boundingBox == null) {
        return contents;
    }
    List<IObject> result = new ArrayList<>();

    // The maximum distance an element can be from the page edge
    double maxEdgeDistance = boundingBox.getHeight() / 5;
    // Maximum gap between consecutive header/footer elements
    double maxGap = boundingBox.getHeight() / 6;

    Double lastEdgeCoordinate = null;
    for (IObject content : contents) {
        double distanceFromEdge;
        double currentEdgeCoordinate;

        if (isHeaderDetection) {
            distanceFromEdge = boundingBox.getHeight() - content.getBottomY();
            currentEdgeCoordinate = content.getBottomY();
        } else {
            distanceFromEdge = content.getTopY();
            currentEdgeCoordinate = content.getTopY();
        }

        // First element must be close to the edge
        if (result.isEmpty() && distanceFromEdge > maxEdgeDistance) {
            continue;
        }

        // Subsequent elements must not have too large a gap from previous
        if (!result.isEmpty()) {
            double gap = Math.abs(currentEdgeCoordinate - lastEdgeCoordinate);
            if (gap > maxGap) {
                break; // stop, don't include any more elements
            }
        }

        result.add(content);
        lastEdgeCoordinate = currentEdgeCoordinate;
    }
    return result;
}
```

Wait, but this changes the semantics. The current code filters each element independently. The gap-based approach breaks as soon as a gap is detected.

Let me reconsider. The candidates list for footers is the sublist of sorted page contents (sorted top-to-bottom). The candidates are the last `currentIndex` elements. Since sorted top-to-bottom, the last elements are at the bottom of the page.

So the candidate list for footers (indexed 0 to n-1):
- Element 0: farthest from bottom (highest in the sorted sublist)
- Element n-1: closest to bottom

For the bug case with currentIndex=2:
- Element 0: body note (topY=135)
- Element 1: actual footer (topY=44)

Wait no — the sublist is from `size-currentIndex` to `size`:
- `pageContents.subList(size-2, size)` = last 2 elements
- Since sorted top-to-bottom, last 2 elements are the bottommost 2
- Element at `size-2`: body note (topY=135) — second from bottom
- Element at `size-1`: actual footer (topY=44) — bottommost

So in the sublist passed to `filterHeaderOrFooterContents`:
- contents.get(0) = body note (topY=135) → farthest from bottom
- contents.get(1) = actual footer (topY=44) → closest to bottom

For my gap-based approach, iterating from contents.get(0):
- Element 0 (body note): distanceFromEdge = 135. If maxEdgeDistance = 140, it passes. But this is wrong — the body note shouldn't be included.

The issue is that the body note IS within the edge distance threshold. So the gap approach would:
- Element 0: accepted (135 < 140)
- Element 1: gap = |44 - 135| = 91 > maxGap (70) → break

But element 0 has already been added! And element 1 (actual footer) would NOT be added. This is backwards.

I need to iterate from closest-to-edge to farthest-from-edge, and break when a gap is detected. But the current iteration goes from farthest to closest.

Alternatively, I could change the iteration order or use a different approach.

Let me reconsider. The simplest approach that would work:

**Check all elements for proximity to the page edge, AND check that the elements as a group are within a certain distance from the page edge.**

For footers:
```java
